subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis:— Morphologically,
Breynia pseudorostrata
is most similar to
B. rostrata Merrill (1927: 346)
, but clearly differs from the latter by having ovate to elliptic (ovate-lanceolate to oblong-lanceolate in
B. rostrata
) leaf blades with broadly rounded to acute apex (acuminate tips in
B. rostrata
), stigmas with 2 shallow and completely inflexed lobes (bifid, sharp, erect in
B. rostrata
), and apex of capsules subtruncate (beaked in
B. rostrata
).
